\begin_layout Subsection
The steps of AHP
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-steps-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve a decision problem by using AHP, we need to decompose the decision
 problem into the following steps 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saaty2008decision,web:goepel_ahp"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
From the decision problem, we define the goal of the problem and determine
 the related elements such as alternatives, criteria, and sub-criteria.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We construct a hierarchy based on the decision problem.
 We put the goal of the decision problem on the first level of the hierarchy.
 Then we put the criteria (and sub-criteria for each criterion) in the intermedi
ate levels.
 Finally, at the last level we put the alternatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On each level of the hierarchy (except the top level), we make pairwise
 comparisons for the criteria, groups of sub-criteria that belongs to a
 particular criterion, and the alternatives with respect to each criterion
 or sub-criterion.
 We use comparison matrices to represent the results of pairwise comparisons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We calculate the priorities or priority vectors from the comparison matrices.
 Also, we should calculate the Consistency Index and Consistency Ratio to
 check if the comparisons are consistent or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We calculate the ranking of alternatives by aggregating priorities from
 criteria, sub-criteria and the alternatives with respect to each criterion
 or sub-criterion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
After obtaining the ranking for the alternatives, we should examine the
 Consistency Index and Consistency Ratio to see if our comparisons are consisten
t or not.
 If not, we need to revise our comparisons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the comparisons are consistent, we can use the ranking of the alternatives
 to select the optimal alternative for our decision problem, i.e.
 the alternative with the highest ranking.
\end_layout

